  <discussion>Encalypta vulgaris has at times been lumped with E. rhaptocarpa, and some “intermediate” specimens are difficult to place.  The absence of a peristome, weakly furrowed capsule, and absence of an awn on vegetative leaves should be sufficient to identify most specimens.  Furthermore, E. vulgaris is most frequently found in the western United States and western Mexico, while E. rhaptocarpa is more common throughout the north in Canada and Alaska.</discussion>
